      "side": 1,
      "message": "Suggest rewriting this whole segment a bit. Right now if temp \u003d \"Playlists/foo\" is entered, then directoryonly \u003d \"Playlists\" and the reload fails.\n\nI\u0027m thinking something along these lines:\n\n  char directoryonly[MAX_PATH+3];\n  directoryonly[0] \u003d \u0027/\u0027; // hack: prepending two slashes simplifies the code\n  directoryonly[1] \u003d \u0027/\u0027;\n  strcpy(directoryonly+2, temp);\n\n  char* filename \u003d strrchr(directoryonly, \u0027/\u0027);\n  *filename \u003d \u0027\\0\u0027;\n  filename +\u003d 1;\n\n  ft_play_playlist(temp, directoryonly, filename, true);\n\nThis hack gives the right filename and directory, but the directory might start with two or three leading slashes in some cases. From my testing, it doesn\u0027t cause problems. It\u0027s not easy to prevent this in general, because users can enter stuff like \"////pl////blegh\". Rockbox seems to ignore redundant separators anyway, following the usual *nix conventions.\n\nThese types of things, are what I hate most in C. The simplest stuff can get so annoying and error prone...",
